{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.19,0.37,0.15,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/353"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3424"},{"type":"tags","id":"7853"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9803"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39731"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents with a ten-year history of intermittent retrosternal pain, worse at night, on bending forward and after large meals. These episodes may last for about an hour and are relieved with antacids. More recently, he has been disturbed by episodes of nocturnal regurgitation and a choking feeling. These symptoms are his main concern. He smokes a packet of cigarettes a day and drinks two cans of beer a day. He has been on pantoprazole (40 mg bd) for two months. Physical examination is unremarkable apart from his BMI of 29. His 24-hour pH profile shows acidification (pH\u0026lt;4.0) of the lower oesophagus for 8% of the time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment to alleviate his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Changing from pantoprazole to esomeprazole","Lose weight, aiming for BMI 18-25","Reduce alcohol consumption and cease smoking","Sleep with the head of his bed propped up","Laparoscopic fundoplication"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIf his symptoms were just those of heartburn i.e. retrosternal chest pain, then modification to his drinking and smoking habits, reducing his weight and trialling a new protein pump inhibitor at maximal medical therapy might be sufficient. However, this patient\u0027s main concern appears to be volume reflux, indicated by his nocturnal regurgitation and choking sensation. Certainly, he should try and comply with all the aforementioned strategies, but even if successful, they are unlikely to have a significant impact on symptom control. To effectively deal with the regurgitation, which is what bothers him rather than any heartburn, he should be offered a procedure that reduces the likelihood of further episodes: \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic fundoplication\u003C/strong\u003E, with success rates as high as 90%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertainly if surgical intervention is agreed upon, this patient must be persuaded to comply with some lifestyle advice and lose some weight before the surgical procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Troublesome volume reflux is best treated by fundoplication."],"references":["Cicala M, Emerenziani S, Guarino MP, Ribolsi M. Proton pump inhibitor resistance, the real challenge in gastro-esophageal reflux disease. World J Gastroenterol. 2013;19(39):6529-35. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24151377/","Lundell L. Laparoscopic fundoplication is the treatment of choice for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Protagonist. Gut. 2002;51(4):468-71. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12235064/","Lafullarde T, Watson DI, Jamieson GG, Myers JC, Game PA, Devitt PG. Laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication: five-year results and beyond. Arch Surg. 2001;136(2):180-4. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11177138/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"353"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49547"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T23:06:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:29:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"353"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64116"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable f